Duckman is Andrew Wolfe, heir to Wolfe Holdings — a Midwestern conglomerate his grandfather built from manufacturing contracts and real estate. Andrew has never been interested in running the company beyond what it funds. He has a board for that.

His parents were killed on his thirteenth birthday during a robbery at a Greenville restaurant. The investigation later revealed the robbery was orchestrated by a crime organization with deep roots in the city's underfunded neighborhoods — a place where people took desperate options because no other options existed. Andrew did not miss this detail. He has spent his adult life uncertain whether he is a hero or someone who needs to feel like one.

He is a skilled detective, martial artist, and self-taught engineer. He designed the Gander himself (with contracted fabrication), and continues to upgrade it. He is also a genuinely gifted investigator — patient, methodical, and comfortable with long silences in interrogation rooms. He solves crimes that the Greenville PD has quietly given up on.

When there's trouble he glides down from the Gander to protect Greenville. He has no superpowers. He has a glide suit, a utility harness, and the kind of preparedness that borders on compulsion.

Duckman is in therapy because his therapist (Dr. Okafor, via Alliance referral) asked him once whether building a recreation center in the neighborhood where his parents died was for the neighborhood or for himself, and he has not stopped thinking about it since. He is not a bad person. He is a person who turned enormous grief into enormous industry and isn't entirely sure whether that counts as healing.

His flying fortress, the Gander, is his personal watchtower, hovering cloaked above Greenville. The entrance is in a replica museum in the river district dedicated to waterfowl migration — Andrew's least subtle joke about himself. Nobody has figured it out.
